Topics Reviewed
Digital Forensics

Evidence Preservation

Ensures integrity of evidence during investigations.

Maintains proper chain of custody.

Critical for legal admissibility and accurate analysis.

Network Monitoring

Firewall / Network Logs

Identify suspicious outbound traffic.

Help detect data exfiltration attempts.

Allow analysts to trace destinations of compromised communications.

Security Testing Governance

Rules of Engagement (RoE)

Define scope, boundaries, and acceptable actions during testing.

Ensure ethical and controlled penetration testing activities.

Endpoint Security

EDR (Endpoint Detection and Response)

Provides visibility into endpoint activity.

Detects anomalies and deviations from normal behavior.

Enables rapid response to threats.

Data Governance

Data Retention

Defines how long data is stored and when it should be deleted.

Reduces unnecessary risk exposure and storage costs.

Malware Techniques

Memory Injection

Allows attackers to execute malicious code in memory.

Often bypasses traditional file-based detection methods.

Especially dangerous in real-time/critical systems.

Threat Actors

Unskilled Attackers (Script Kiddies)

Typically seek recognition rather than financial gain.

Use publicly available tools to exploit vulnerabilities.

Email Security

Email Traffic Scanning

Detects malicious attachments and links before reaching users.

Helps prevent phishing and malware infections.

Incident Response

Detection Phase

First phase in incident response.

Identifies potential security incidents via monitoring and alerts.

Legacy System Risks

Legacy systems:

Often lack updates and modern protections.

May become single points of failure.

Require compensating controls to maintain security and availability.

